  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2273357825" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2273357825" />
    <a title="Tony P" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/63103702-tony-p"><img alt="Tony P" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1556757522p2/63103702.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2273357825?book_show_action=true">Jan 26, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tony P" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tony P" href="/user/show/63103702-tony-p">Tony P</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2273357825" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9840558881711190237">I think this series has suffered more criticism than it deserves. Whenever I have trouble rating a book, especially by a good author whose other books I rate highly, I ask myself, What was the author trying to achieve? Did he/she succeed? I also bear in mind that a book may work on several levels, which appeal to different people: one person may like Heinlein for his excellent adventures, while another may be uninterested in the suspense but delighted by the philosophy. It is pointless criticizi</span>
  <span id="freeText9840558881711190237" style="display:none">I think this series has suffered more criticism than it deserves. Whenever I have trouble rating a book, especially by a good author whose other books I rate highly, I ask myself, What was the author trying to achieve? Did he/she succeed? I also bear in mind that a book may work on several levels, which appeal to different people: one person may like Heinlein for his excellent adventures, while another may be uninterested in the suspense but delighted by the philosophy. It is pointless criticizing a space-opera for a lack of character development. <br /><br />With that in mind, I think Helliconia Spring succeeds very well. In many ways, it follows the hard SF tradition of Hal Clements: Build a world of extreme conditions, justify its physics, people it with creatures more or less like us in thought &amp; feeling, and see what happens. <br /><br />Although this is "hard" SF in its attention to physical detail, Helliconia Spring also has some qualities of high fantasy. There is no Dark Lord or Good vs Evil, but there is plenty of Sword if not Sorcery. In some ways — its epic scale, the extreme seasons, the attention to detail — it is comparable to George R R Martin's later A Song of Ice and Fire (Game of Thrones). Aldiss himself says in the Preface to a retrospective collection of his short stories that the border between fantasy and SF in his writing is fuzzy; some stories which he wrote as fantasy he now regards as SF, and vice versa. <br /><br />The only slightly jarring note in this book is the team of human observers in the orbiting habitat Avernus. In this book, it seems superfluous. It becomes more important in the sequels. <br /><br />If I don't give this book 5 stars, it is for two reasons: the length and the large, multi-generation cast of characters is somewhat overwhelming; and the heavy use of neologisms and technical language (especially geology), makes reading a bit heavy going. Still, this is an excellent book by a top author, and I enjoyed it very much. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9840558881711190237" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


